NECROTIZING FASCIITIS - AUSTRALIA: (VICTORIA) STREPTOCOCCUS GROUP A, INVASIVE, INFANT, ALERT, REQUEST FOR INFORMATION
**********************************************************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Tue 11 May 2021 5:22 PM AEST
Source: News [edited]
https://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/health/health-problems/melbourne-toddler-almost-loses-her-leg-to-strep-a-as-vaccines-are-trialled/news-story/904575ab69302578b6c0f4b2893f846f


An alert has been issued after 3 suburbs in Melbourne recorded cases of flesh-eating skin disease. A Melbourne toddler came close to losing her leg after contracting a flesh-eating infection caused by Strep A [_Streptococcus pyogenes_ or Group A streptococcus (GAS)].

[The child] was just 11 months old when she suffered from a bout of colds that lasted for about a month. The child had a fever and was taken to hospital where she was diagnosed with the bacteria that was affecting her limb. Luckily, doctors were able to save her leg, but the youngster's right calf was scarred. "It was a very precarious point in her life," [her mother] said.

According to the Murdoch Children's Research Institute (MCRI), 750 million people are impacted by the disease, which kills more than 500 000 people around the world every year. The illness [GAS infection] can cause acute rheumatic fever, heart disease, kidney disease, and toxic shock syndrome. Young children, the elderly, and pregnant women are susceptible to the bug.

Dr Josh Osowicki from MCRI told 7 NEWS the [bacterium] needs a vaccine. The medical institute is trialling vaccines and new treatments. Part of the study involves deliberately infecting healthy adult volunteers with the germ [GAS] in a controlled environment.

[Byline: Belinda Palmada]

